<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-757-344  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 757 344.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Engineering  August 1990 v22 n8 p20(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Are you a good decision maker? (Competitive Edge) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ransom, William J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Guidelines for improving the decision-making process inengineering environments are presented.andP;  Decisions should be basedon available information; when the information changes a goodmanagement practice is to review the decision and alter it ifnecessary.andP;  Decision making is a process that begins with definingthe problem and identifying its root causes.andP;  Problems most oftensurface when expectations and reality are not the same, or whenthe organization is not where management wants it to be.andP;  Before aproblem can be solved, management must develop a commonunderstanding of the situation.andP;  Once a problem has been defined,facts must be gathered before a solution can be offered.andP;  'Whatif' questions should then be used to consider various solutions.andO;The final step in decision making is implementation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Decision-makingGuidelinesEngineeringManagement StyleProblem Solving.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>